right-wing Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
 The Republicans' letter to President Clinton came two days after Elders, 
according to newspaper accounts, referred to the "un-Christian religious right" 
and added: "We've got to be strong to take on those people who are selling our 
children out in the name of religion." 
</P>
<P>
 The letter did not specifically mention these remarks, but they were cited at 
a news conference by Rep. Cliff Stearns (R-Fla.), the author of the letter, and 
by other lawmakers and spokesmen for conservative Christian organizations. 
</P>
<P>
 "She should be using this office to fight sickness and disease and not using 
this office to fight parents and churches," Stearns said. 
</P>
<P>
