<HEADLINE>
<P>
RIGHTS OF GAYS AND LESBIANS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 I enjoyed the article "Spirit of Achievement Marks Gay Pride Parade" (June 
13). However, the writer made one statement in the article that wasn't entirely 
correct. Referring to the Stonewall riot in June, 1969, she wrote that it "gave 
birth to the fledgling gay and lesbian civil rights movement." 
</P>
<P>
 While the Stonewall riot is one of the most important events, and surely a 
major turning point in the fight for gay rights, it was hardly the beginning of 
it. Here in Los Angeles, Vice Versa, the first magazine for lesbians, began 
publication in 1947; Physique Pictorial, a magazine for gay men, started in 
1951; ONE magazine was also started in 1951 and was seized by the post office, 
which led to a groundbreaking Supreme Court decision in 1958, which said that 
ONE served the needs of the gay community, and therefore was not pornographic. 
The Advocate, now the nation's oldest gay publication, was started in 1967. The 
Mattachine Society, the country's first influential gay rights organization, 
was formed in 1950. There was a gay Christian church in L.A. as far back as 
1956, and Metropolitan Community Church, now the world's largest gay church, 
was established in 1968. L.A. had its own share of gay rights protests in the 
1960s, most notably in January, 1966, after the LAPD raided a couple of gay 
bars on Sunset Boulevard. 
</P>
<P>
 To say that the Stonewall riot was the start of lesbian and gay rights is a 
disservice to all the brave men and women who lived openly and fought for gay 
and lesbian rights in the decades before Stonewall, risking their freedom, 
livelihood and lives. 
</P>
<P>
 G.L. LEYNER 
</P>
<P>
 Northridge 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 * All right, out with it. Do the homosexuals have an agenda for the domestic 
partnership bill (June 9)? It's no secret. This bill is another steppingstone 
toward full civil rights for lesbian and gay people. Gays and lesbians need 
this bill more than heterosexual couples who choose not to marry. As those who 
oppose the bill are quick to point out: Heterosexual couples can marry if they 
choose, and anyone can make out a will and appoint a conservator through the 
durable power of attorney for health care and finances. Homosexuals do not 
enjoy the right to marry their life partners or to have their relationships 
recognized by the state. 
</P>
<P>
 MADELYNN RIGOPOULOS 
</P>
<P>
 Huntington Beach 
</P>
</TEXT>
