<HEADLINE>
<P>
GOLF, BASKETBALL DESERVED BETTER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 To whom it may concern at ABC: 
</P>
<P>
 After avidly following your exclusive coverage of the U.S. Open, I was 
appalled when you switched during the sudden-death playoff to the O.J. Simpson 
arraignment while every other station covered the same thing. 
</P>
<P>
 You had the only exclusive audience on television and you blew it. 
</P>
<P>
 WILLIAM L. BORDWELL 
</P>
<P>
 Pasadena 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 My reaction to the preemption of the NBA playoff game by TV coverage of O.J. 
Simpson's procession from Orange County to his home was that seldom in history 
has more time and effort been expended by anything less significant. I thought 
that at least The Times would be more professional in its coverage. What I saw 
Saturday morning was about half of the first section of the newspaper devoted 
to the subject. It seems that the media has lost all sense of perspective. 
</P>
<P>
 KARL G. BLAKE 
</P>
<P>
 Westlake Village 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 It is difficult to fathom the mind-boggling events concerning the O.J. Simpson 
tragedy. I know I feel a deep sense of sadness for Nicole Brown Simpson and 
Ronald Goldman, and sympathy for their families. As for O.J., I just don't want 
to believe that he could commit such a horrific act. I know that some of the 
evidence seems compelling, but let's not forget that stranger things have 
happened than the possibility of Simpson's innocence. As for his questionable 
conduct, I think you'd have to walk a mile in O.J.'s cleats before you get the 
answer to those questions. Even then you'll probably only discover that you're 
walking in some pretty big cleats. 
</P>
<P>
 DOUG M. LITTLETON 
</P>
<P>
 San Marino 
</P>
