<HEADLINE>
<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: BOYLE HEIGHTS; PARENTS 
AT SCHOOL WIN FIGHT FOR SUMMER VACATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The parents at Euclid Avenue Elementary School got their way after all -- the 
school will use a traditional summer vacation calendar. 
</P>
<P>
 The Boyle Heights school became the focus of controversy in April for using a 
voting system in which each teacher's ballot counted for 6.32 votes and each 
parent's counted for one.The teachers, who wanted a year-round calendar, used 
their votes to overrule the parents' desire for a summer vacation. 
</P>
<P>
 In a new election Thursday night in which a one-person, one-vote rule was 
used, an overwhelming majority of parents approved the traditional schedule. 
The Euclid episode had become a flash-point for many parents who say their 
voices are muted in shaping Los Angeles Unified School District policy. To help 
resolve the dispute, the district brought in professional mediators. 
</P>
