<HEADLINE>
<P>
BUYUKUNCU SETS RECORD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ERIK HAMILTON, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Irvine Novaquatics Coach Dave Salo told Derya Buyukuncu that if New York lost 
the NBA championship series, he would owe Buyukuncu $50. But if the Knicks won, 
the Turkish Olympian would owe him a 2:01 in the 200-meter backstroke at the 
Swim Meet of Champions. That was two weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
 Salo is out $50, but he did get from Buyukuncu a performance of 2 minutes 
01.77 seconds in the event, good enough for a meet record Friday, the second 
day of competition at the Marguerite Aquatics Complex. 
</P>
<P>
 In Friday's preliminaries, Buyukuncu had the second-fastest time behind 
Stanford's Jeff Rouse. But Buyukuncu said he was holding back, saving his best 
for the finals. 
</P>
<P>
 "I just wanted to swim as fast as I could go and get the meet record," 
Buyukuncu said. "But I mean, I was up against Rouse. He has the world record in 
the 100 back. But I didn't want that to interfere with my race." 
</P>
<P>
 Buyukuncu's swim shattered the mark of 2:15.32, set by Royce Sharp of 
Stanford. 
</P>
<P>
 In addition to his 200 back victory, Buyukuncu, who was The Times Orange 
County swimmer of the year, took first in the 100-meter freestyle (51.60), 
defeating Steve Vandermeulen of the University of Calgary. 
</P>
<P>
 To no one's surprise, Janet Evans won the 400 freestyle (4:13.24), swimming 
seven seconds faster than her time in the preliminaries, and finishing 10 
seconds ahead of runner-up Lisa Jacob. Chad Carvin won the men's event in 
3:57.47. 
</P>
<P>
 Cheryl Murphy, 16, of Mission Viejo High and the Nadodores, was able to hold 
on to defeat Kathy Monar of the University of Calgary in the 200 backstroke, 
posting a 2:19.25. 
</P>
<P>
 Ugar Tanner of the Chinook Swim Club won the men's 200-meter butterfly in 
2:03.69. Angie Wester-Krieg of Stanford won the women's event in 2:13.61. 
</P>
<P>
 In the women's 400-meter freestyle relay, the Trojan Swim Club just touched 
out Stanford in 3:56.56. Stanford's men defeated Calgary by a second, posting a 
3:31.17. 
</P>
<P>
 Competition resumes at 9 a.m. today with finals scheduled to begin at 5 p.m. 
</P>
</TEXT>
