ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: TUSTIN; VOTERS TO DECIDE ON COUNCIL TERM LIMITS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALAN EYERLY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 City voters will decide in November if council members should be limited to 
serving two terms. 
</P>
<P>
 But Mayor Thomas R. Saltarelli and Councilman Jeffrey Thomas said they believe 
voters should be given the option of choosing between two-term or three-term 
limits for council members. 
</P>
<P>
 They said that the city will have less clout on county and regional boards 
that operate on a seniority basis if council members are limited to two terms. 
A full term lasts four years. 
</P>
<P>
 The City Council this week voted 4 to 0 to approve a measure that will allow 
voters to decide on the two-term limit. Saltarelli and Thomas joined council 
members Jim Potts and Michael J. Doyle in voting for the measure. Councilwoman 
Tracy Worley was absent. ALAN EYERLY 
</P>
