<HEADLINE>
<P>
GARDEN GROVE SCHOOLS BUDGET MAKES NO CUTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JON NALICK 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The governing board of the Garden Grove Unified School District approved its 
1994-95 budget, a $178.9-million spending plan that maintains all current 
programs and staffing levels. 
</P>
<P>
 The Board of Education unanimously approved the budget without comment during 
its regular meeting this week. 
</P>
<P>
 District officials said they avoided having to make cuts in spite of 
inadequate state funding partly because they often left vacant positions open 
to save money and encouraged school administrators to reduce expenses whenever 
possible. 
</P>
<P>
 "The district is doing OK. We're holding our own," despite this being the 
fifth consecutive year with no increase in revenue from the state, said Art 
Becker, district business manager. Based on current projections of state 
funding, "we believe we can run the same program next year as this year," he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 The district is the second largest in the county, serving about 42,000 
students. The district covers most of Garden Grove and parts of Westminster, 
Cypress, Stanton, Santa Ana, Anaheim and Fountain Valley.JON NALICK 
</P>
